User Guide for shinyGEM

O’Connor G, Melton P, Huang RC, Lin A, Nair G, Rauschert S

28 November 2019


Introduction

This project is based on the GEM (gene, environment, methylation) package, developed by Hong P. et al.(2016). The GEM package uses the MatrixEQTL package from Shabalin A.

We aimed to build an easy to use package for wider application in the research community, enabling non-bioinformaticians to perform epigenome/genome wide association studies.

The package includes two main functions. One to perform an EWAS in terminal or in RStudio, the other one to perform the analysis in a graphical user interface.

To use the terminal based program, use the following function:

  • shinyGEM_Emodel()

To start the interactive graphical user interface, type the following in the R console or in RStudio:

  • shinyGEM()

How to

Installation

The package requires the devtools package, which is not always installed on Windows machines. Install the devtools package the following way:

install.packages("devtools")

After successful installation, you can now proceed to install the shinyGEM package:

devtools::install_github("Hobbeist/shinyGEM", build_vignettes=T)

Basic example

Lets assume you have an epigenetic data set on the same computer/virtual machine, that you are using R/RStudio on. The data should look something like this:

Methylation data

The methylation data needs to be in the following format:

  • columns: IDs
  • rows: CpG identifiers

Note: the function shinyGEM_Emodel() will handle the reformatting of the data for modelling. This includes making the first column the rownames of the data.

Covariate data

The covariate data needs to contain the same participant IDs as the DNA methylation data. the shinyGEM_Emodel() function will automatically select the overlapping IDs between the two data sets and arrange the data accordingly, as the IDs need to be in the same order in both data sets.

Important note: The shinyGEM model only takes numerical variables as input, so make sure all variabels are represented by numbers, which is especially important for categorical variables.

This does not apply for the batch variable (Plate_no in the example), as this variable will only be used for the batch correction, leveraging the sva packages Combat method.

Note: As the methylation data frame will be severa gigabyte large, it is not necessary to load the data frames into R before modelling. The shinyGEM_Emodel() function take the path to both the covariate and the epigenetic data files as arguments and loads them.

Model the data

When you made sure that the covariate and the methylation data are in the format as above, you can start with the model. We will use the terminal/R code first, before diving into the user interface.

The function we will use is:
shinyGEM_Emodel(envFileName, methylFileName,predictorName, batchName = FALSE, covName = NULL, qqplotInclude = TRUE)

For this function, we need to specify the following:

envFileName: This is the path to the covaraite and predictor data frame (covar above)

methylFileName: Just like for the covariates file, here we need to specify the path for the methylation data

predictorName: This is a character, naming the the predictor variabel for our model, e.g. preg_smoking in our data example

batchName: A character naming the batch variable for batch correction, e.g. Plate_no in our example. Note: if this stays FALSE, batch correction will not be included

covName: Here teh user can specify a covariate variable or a vector of covariates to be included in the model. Note: the covariates all need to be numeric, as noted above.

qqplotInclude: By default, teh modelling process will include a qqplot of the p-values.

Note: to store the model results (a list of the result table and the qqplot), don’t forget to assign it, like so:

resultsEWAS <- shinyGEM_Emodel(envFileName, methylFileName,predictorName, batchName = FALSE, covName = NULL, qqplotInclude = TRUE))

#setwd("~/Desktop/")
results <- shinyGEM_Emodel(envFileName = "~/Desktop/covar_2.txt", 
                           methylFileName = "~/Desktop/meth_2.txt", 
                           predictorName = "preg_smoking")
## 100.00% done, 1,000 CpGs
## Analysis done in:  0.105  seconds

The qqplot:

results$qqPlot

Visualization

The package contains a fucntion to create a volcano plot. It works in the following way:

VolcanoPlot(results$resultTable, title="Volcano Plot: Smoking during Pregnancy")

The Shiny app

For users that are not too comfortable with the terminal environment or coding in R, the package includes a shiny app. This app can easily be started by typing shinyGEM() in the R console.

This will open up the following window:

Fig 1: The shiny interface

On the lefthandside, click “Dashboard”, to get to the applciation screen:

Fig 2: Select input

First, we need to select the methylation data set on the file browser:

Fig 3: Select methylation file

Second, , we need to select the covariate data set on the file browser. Here, we also get prompted to select a predictor variable and covariates, if desired:

Fig 4: Select covariate file

After this, we need to make some selection before we model: Do we want to adjust for batch? Do we give the Volcano plot a distinct header?

Fig 6: Final settings

After pressing the “Start GEM Model” button, we have to wait a bit until we get the result output: a volcano plot and the result table. Both can be downloaded via the app.

Fig 6: Final settings
